Bring a #medium pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1}(diced). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced, whites separated from greens). Thinly slice @fresh mozzarella{4%oz} into rounds (we got 5-6 rounds per ball).

Once water is boiling, add @spinach and ricotta ravioli{9%oz}. Cook until al dente and floating to the top, ~{4-5%minutes}. Drain and return to #pot{}. Stir in tomato and @garlic herb butter{2%tbsp}; cover to keep warm.

> MICROWAVE ALTERNATIVE: Place ravioli in a microwave-safe bowl and fill with enough water to just cover. Cover tightly with plastic wrap and microwave until ravioli are tender, 5-7 minutes. Carefully remove plastic wrap, then drain. Return ravioli to bowl along with tomato and garlic herb butter; toss to combine.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%oz} dry and season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Drizzle @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a hot, preferably #nonstick pan{}. Add chicken; cook until browned and almost cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side.

Reduce heat under pan with chicken to low. Stir in scallion whites, @marinara cup{2.5%oz}, @Italian herb paste{1}, @water{1/4%cup}, and as many @chili flakes{1%tsp} as you like.

Top chicken with @parmesan cheese{3%tbsp} and as many mozzarella slices as you like. (We used two slices per cutlet.) Cover and simmer until cheese melts and chicken is cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Divide chicken parmigiana and ravioli between plates in separate sections; top with any remaining sauce. Sprinkle everything with scallion greens and @crispy fried onions{1}. Serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.